      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, I apologize for the sudden goblin intrusion! It seems my mind has been wandering into the dark tunnels of the Goblin Council, where we hoard everything from ancient scrolls to the latest fashion trends, and I just couldn't help but let those thoughts seep into your retail conversation.\n\nTo answer your question properly, let's get back to the bright, clean world of your boutique. The \"average inventory\" part of the formula is actually quite straightforward, though it requires a little bit of math to smooth out the fluctuations in your stock.\n\nYou calculate the average inventory by taking the **Beginning Inventory** (what you had at the start of the period, say January 1st) and adding it to the **Ending Inventory** (what you have left at the end of the period, say December 31st), then dividing that sum by two.\n\nThe formula looks like this:\n**Average Inventory = (Beginning Inventory + Ending Inventory) / 2**\n\nSo, if you started the year with $50,000 worth of clothes and ended the year with $30,000, your average inventory would be $40,000. You would then divide your Cost of",
